The '''Académie André Delvaux''' is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] professional organisation dedicated to the promotion and development of [[Cinema of Belgium|Belgian cinema]]. Founded in 2010, it is responsible for the annual [[Magritte Awards]], Belgium's principal film awards.
==History== The Académie André Delvaux was founded by two associations: the Francophone Film Producers Association (UPFF), represented by Patrick Quinet, [[Marion Hänsel]], Olivier Bronckart and Philippe Kauffmann, and the association of authors Pro Spère, represented by Luc Jabon, André Buytaers, Benoît Coppée and Alok Nandi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academieandredelvaux.com/_downloads/download.php?file=20_101028_Satuts_AAD.pdf|title=Annexes du Moniteur belge|publisher=Académie André Delvaux|format=PDF|date=October 28, 2010|accessdate=January 9, 2012|language=French}}</ref> Its name was chosen in honour of the Belgian film director [[André Delvaux]] (1926–2002). The academy aims to promote the Belgian [[film industry]] around the globe. Its main task is to organize the [[Magritte Awards]], replacing the [[Joseph Plateau Award]], awarded from 1985 to 2006. Charly Herscovici, who created the foundation Magritte, allowed the academy to use the name of [[René Magritte]] for the awards.
The board of directors of the academy is composed of Luc Jabon (Pro Spère), Patrick Quinet (Union des producteurs de films francophones), Frédéric Delcor ([[French Community of Belgium|Fédération Wallonie-Bruxelles]], Centre du Cinéma et de l'Audiovisuel), Nicole Gillet ([[Festival International du Film Francophone de Namur]]), Philippe Reynaert (Wallimage), Philippe Logie ([[BeTV (Belgium)|BeTV]]), [[Jaco Van Dormael]] and Dan Cukier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academieandredelvaux.com/home.php?lang=fr|title=Académie André Delvaux|publisher=Académie André Delvaux|accessdate=January 9, 2012|language=French}}</ref>
The [[1st Magritte Awards]] ceremony took place on 5 February 2011 at the [[Square – Brussels Meeting Centre|Square]] in the historic site of [[Mont des Arts]], [[Brussels]]. Twenty categories were presented, honoring artists, directors and other personalities of the filmmaking industry of the time for their works during the 2009–2010 period.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.moniteurdufilm.be/?article=77&PHPSESSID=d0636412b8c21fa5e4cc15a80ae5ad53 |title=Le cinéma belge était à l’honneur lors de la Première édition des Magritte du cinéma belge francophone |work=Moniteur du film |accessdate=January 9, 2012 |language=French |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205055415/http://www.moniteurdufilm.be/?article=77&PHPSESSID=d0636412b8c21fa5e4cc15a80ae5ad53 |archivedate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>
