'''Pura Vida Bracelets''' is a [[La Jolla, California]]-based company that sells hand-crafted bracelets online and through boutique stores. It was founded in 2010 by Griffin Thall and Paul Goodman, who discovered the bracelets while on a vacation in [[Costa Rica]]. After a number of celebrities were spotted wearing the product, interest increased, and the company has since sold over 2 million bracelets. Pura Vida partners with a number of charities, producing bracelets in those charities' colors and donating a portion of those bracelets' sale prices back towards the partner charities.
==About== "Pura Vida" means "pure life" in Spanish. Pura Vida Bracelets is a retailer that sells bracelets that are hand-made in [[Costa Rica]]. The company, which is based in [[La Jolla, California]], was founded by Griffin Thall and Paul Goodman in 2010.<ref name=RYOT_15MAY9>{{cite web|last1=Todorovic|first1=Stefan|title=From Passion to Profits: Pura Vida Bracelets|url=http://www.ryot.org/pura-vida-bracletes/930976|website=Ryot|accessdate=13 January 2016|date=9 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228101830/http://www.ryot.org/pura-vida-bracletes/930976#|archive-date=2015-12-28|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Thall and Goodman traveled to Costa Rica together on vacation after graduating from [[San Diego State University]], where they met a pair of bracelet makers and purchased 400 bracelets for $100 to bring back to the United States. The pair sold their original stock at small stores in the [[Malibu, California]], area.<ref name=PATCH_11JUNE28>{{cite web|last1=Reverente|first1=Mira Del Fonso|title=Pura Vida Bracelets: Beyond the Fashion Trend|url=http://patch.com/california/agourahills/pura-vida-bracelets-beyond-the-fashion-trend|website=Patch: Agoura Hills|publisher=Patch Media|accessdate=13 January 2016|date=28 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=KABC_15FEB13>{{cite web|last1=Elex|first1=Michaelson|title=SoCal entrepreneurs make millions selling bracelets for charity|url=http://abc7.com/society/socal-entrepreneurs-make-millions-selling-bracelets-for-charity/504844/|website=[[KABC-TV]]|accessdate=13 January 2016|date=13 February 2015}}</ref> After a number of celebrities &ndash; including reality television personality [[Lauren Conrad]], soccer player [[David Beckham]], and musicians [[Rihanna]] and [[Skrillex]] &ndash; were seen with the bracelets, Pura Vida saw an increase in web traffic and sales.<ref name=KABC_15FEB13 /> By late 2013, Pura Vida had grown to a dozen US-based staff and 50 Costa Rica-based staff.<ref name=CSM_13DEC2>{{cite web|last1=Karas|first1=David|title=Pura Vida Bracelets creates jobs, funds good works|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Making-a-difference/Change-Agent/2013/1202/Pura-Vida-Bracelets-creates-jobs-funds-good-works|website=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|accessdate=13 January 2016|date=2 December 2013}}</ref> By the end of 2015, the number of Costa Rica-based employees had doubled to over 100.<ref name=BLOG_15NOV17>{{cite web|last1=Fujii|first1=Shanna|title=Growing Your Business & Giving Back ft. Pura Vida Bracelet|url=https://www.bloguettes.com/growing-your-business-and-giving-back-ft-pura-vida-bracelets/|website=Bloguettes|accessdate=13 January 2016|date=17 November 2015}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> As of March 2015, Pura Vida moved 125,000 bracelets a month through 3,400 physical retail outlets and through their website.<ref name=KNSD_15MAR23>{{cite web|last1=Hansen|first1=Bob|title=Young entrepreneurs at 24-year low, one successful business profiled: Pura Vida Bracelets|url=http://www.wptv.com/money/consumer/young-entrepreneurs-at-24-year-low-one-successful-business-profiled-pura-vida-bracelets|website=[[KNSD]]|accessdate=13 January 2016|date=23 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127032432/http://www.wptv.com/money/consumer/young-entrepreneurs-at-24-year-low-one-successful-business-profiled-pura-vida-bracelets#|archive-date=2016-01-27|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> As of February 2015, over two million bracelets have been sold.<ref name="KABC_15FEB13" /> [[Culture of Costa Rica#Pura vida|Pura vida]] means "pure life" in Spanish; in Costa Rica it is said frequently and has many meanings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://costarica.com/culture/national-motto/|title=National Motto|last=Van Velzer|first=Ryan|date=June 21, 2015|work=costarica.com|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> In an interview, Thall and Goodman called the term "the slogan of Costa Rica, just like the word 'aloha' from Hawaii".<ref name=BLOG_15NOV17 />
Pura Vida also creates bracelets for charitable organizations, as a [[cause marketing]] fundraiser; bracelets are produced in a charitable organization's colors, and a portion of the sale of those bracelets goes to that charitable organization.<ref name=KABC_15FEB13 /> As of November 2015, over $600,000 has been donated to charitable organizations;<ref name=BLOG_15NOV17 /> over 175 charities have been the beneficiaries of this program.<ref name=CSM_13DEC2 /> In the aftermath of the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]], Pura Vida sold a memorial bracelet and was able to provide $30,000 to the memorial fund.<ref name=CSM_13DEC2 /> In addition to producing its own line of products, Pura Vida produces bracelets for the [[MyIntent Project]].<ref name=JCK_15DEC24>{{cite web|last1=Vesilind|first1=Emili|title=How a $12 String Bracelet Became a Huge Deal|url=http://www.jckonline.com/2015/12/24/how-12-string-bracelet-became-huge-deal|website=JCK|publisher=[[RELX Group|Reed Exhibitions]]|accessdate=17 January 2016|date=24 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130233925/http://www.jckonline.com/2015/12/24/how-12-string-bracelet-became-huge-deal#|archive-date=2016-01-30|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
